But having attained his end in this he proceeds, finding a means to aſperſe him with a cenſure of abſolute ignorance in the Mathematicks: where that the Reader may ſee Mr. Whites malitious way of proceeding, he muſt know that Gulden (as we ſhall preſently hear in his own words) having (before the printing or publiſhing the often mentioned Demonſtration of the Spiral) diſcovered by help of a Friend an errour therein, thought good notwithſtanding to print it, not as a true one, but as erroneus. This he performs in c. 2. lib. 2. and preſently c. 3. ſhews and refutes all the particular errours committed in c. 2. to the end that others advertiſed of the errours

 committed in cap. 2. might beware of committing the like; 
                  Ʋt ſciant (ſaith he) ſibi cavere à ſcopulis.
